We can use this formula for the value of the new system:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Value of new system}&=\dfrac{\text{Number of branches} \times (\text{Average payment}-\text{Cost}) \times \text{Annuity factor}}{1-\text{Rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

As we can see there is a denominator in this formula. This takes the delay into consideration. 

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Value of new system}&=\dfrac{4\times (\$207,000-\text{Cost})\times 14.012}{1-0.00013}\\[15 pt]
&=\dfrac{\$11,601,936-56.048 \times \text{Cost}}{0.99987}
\end{aligned}$$

We can now equate this to the value of the present system to solve for the value of the cost.
